# On the Riemann Hypothesis

The Riemann Hypothesis remains one of the most important unsolved problems in mathematics. While I can't provide a solution (as none has been verified), I can explain what would be involved:

The hypothesis states that all non-trivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function ζ(s) lie on the critical line where the real part of s equals 1/2.

To solve it, one would need to either:

1. Prove that all non-trivial zeros do indeed lie on this critical line
2. Find a counterexample (a non-trivial zero not on the critical line)

Approaches that mathematicians have explored include:
- Connections to random matrix theory
- Studying the distribution of prime numbers
- Examining related L-functions
- Using spectral theory

This problem has resisted solution for over 160 years despite intensive efforts by many brilliant mathematicians. A verified solution would be revolutionary in number theory and earn you the $1 million Clay Mathematics Institute prize.

